Top Ten Tech Figures of 2010 | PCMag.com





























































































































































































Subscribe




















PCMag Staff


Top Ten Tech Figures of 2010




Reviews/
Software/

Top Ten Tech Figures of 2010





View As: One PageSlides










1



Share
Tweet
Pin
Email

1. Mark Zuckerberg, Facebook

Facebook's 26-year-old founder and CEO spent part of 2010 trying to burnish his image, appearing on Oprah, donating funds to New Jersey schools, but none of that made him particularly important. Zuckerberg is a top tech personality because virtually everything his company does impacts a half billion people.

Facebook is turning into one of the most important platforms on the Web and in computing in general. It takes some work to find someone who is not using the social network. The service has billions of eyeballs, is valued at somewhere around $50 billion, and spent much of the year laying the groundwork to expand well beyond a place to post updates about your cat.

Behind every move and update is the often unblinking Zuckerberg, a somewhat unknowable personality whose early life has already been depicted in a feature-length film. What will he do for his second act? Where will he take Facebook in 2011 and beyond? And will there be a sequel? Lance Ulanoff







2



Share
Tweet
Pin
Email

2. Julian Assange, WikiLeaks

Mark Zuckerberg and Steve Jobs may have burned their fair share of bridges over the years (as countless open letters, tweets, and a major motion picture can attest), but there's no single figure in the tech sphere quite so polarizing as Julian Assange.

To some, the WikiLeaks founder is a modern-day Robin Hood, shining disinfecting sunlight on harmful government secrets. To others, he's one of the most harmful men in the world today, having been branded a "terrorist" by a number of high-profile politicians.

Launched in 2006, Assange's whistle-blowing site came to prominence with the release of formerly classified information about political assignations and U.S. Army protocols at Guantanamo Bay. Over the next couple of years, the leaks continued, but it's 2010 that will surely go down as the year of WikiLeaks. The site has revealed hundreds of thousands of pages of documents, including information about the Iraq War deemed "the largest leak of classified documents in its history." In November, the site released 251,000 U.S. diplomatic cables.

Both the site and its Australian-born founder have been the target of countless attacks, both at the hands of politicians who have called for his arrest and companies that have frozen support for the site. Though even as Assange was arrested on sexual assault charges in early December, a number of high-profile supporters like Michael Moore, Ken Loach, and journalist John Pilger have come to his aid. WikiLeaks, meanwhile, has promised to carry on Assange's work after his arrest. Brian Heater







3



Share
Tweet
Pin
Email

3. Steve Jobs, Apple

Apple's rock star CEO has certainly had a great year, though there were times it could have gone either way. It's been quietly forgotten, but the tech community was decidedly unimpressed with the iPad when it was first announced in January. But while geeks piled on (some calling the tablet merely an extra-large iPod Touch), Jobs ignored them, launched an across-the-board marketing campaign, and convinced more than 8 million people to pick one up.

Then in the spring, when Apple's cone of silence and security was finally  and spectacularly  penetrated by notorious tech blog Gizmodo, it didn't seem to affect the company at all. Apple still sold millions of iPhone 4s, shrugged off the clamor of complaints about the antenna, and saw its stock price soar. Now with the Mac App Store, Jobs is poised to reinvent yet another consumer-tech paradigm: how PC software is bought and sold.

Despite setbacks (MobileMe and Apple TV have yet to prove themselves worthy of the brand), Jobs and Apple come out on top so often because they know who they're doing this for, and it isn't tech geeks, bloggers, or pundits. It's anyone who ever bought a device and said, "Why is this thing beeping at me?" The cure, as Apple sees it, is its sexy, intuitive line of products that "just work," and under Jobs' stewardship the company added handsomely to its arsenal in 2010.Peter Pachal







4



Share
Tweet
Pin
Email

4. Dennis Crowley, FourSquare

Love it or hate it, it's hard to underestimate the effect Foursquare has had on the Web in 2010. The service has more than five million users and is adding 180,000 new ones every 10 days or so. Facebook Places offers similar functionality and Gowallla is increasingly popular among the Technorati, but Foursquare remains the leading location-based service in terms of both new users and new ideas. Its co-founder and CEO Dennis Crowley is a big reason why.

FourSquare isn't Crowley's first stab at a location-based mobile service. He launched a service called Dodgeball in 2000, which let you broadcast your location to a group of friends using your mobile phone. Crowley sold Dodgeball to Google in 2005 and from that point on the service went precisely nowhere. Google shut it down completely in 2010. Google's loss was Crowley's gain. He launched Foursquare at SXSW in March 2009 and has been logging check-ins and awarding badges ever since.

On its surface, Foursquare is just another check-in service. Visit a bar, restaurant, or the office coffee machine enough times and you can get a badge, maybe even become mayor. But this, as Crowley knows, is just a gimmick. It's a little virtual game that, although addictive, doesn't provide a real payoff. That's going to change.

Foursquare offers businesses an unprecedented way of tracking and interacting with customers. The platform can be used a de facto loyalty program. Buy nine coffees at the same shop and your 10th is free. It can also help drive retail sales. Check-in at one location, and you can be alerted to sales nearby. The possibilities are endless, and Crowley seems to have the formula right. There still need to be more incentives for users to participate, but so far he's succeeding where both Google and Facebook have failed. When it comes to location-based services, Dennis Crowley knows where things are heading. Dan Costa









5



Share
Tweet
Pin
Email

5. Steve Ballmer, Microsoft

Since the departure of visionary Bill Gates from day-to-day operations in 2008, Microsoft has been left in the hands of the very different, hard-driving style of Steve Ballmer. Most famously hollering "Developers, Developers, Developers" repeatedly at a company conference, Ballmer has settled down some, but remains a force to reckon with. Struggling to keep Microsoft relevant in the face of attacks from one side from Apple and on the other side from Google, Ballmer's company has enjoyed some turnaround successes of late.

The widespread adoption of Windows 7 seems to have erased the Vista fiasco, even while Apple surpassed Microsoft in market capitalization this year and delivered a sound victory in the tablet market  which Microsoft has been pursuing for a decade  with its iPad. Ballmer has plans for a counterattack, though, as widespread reports claim that Microsoft will show a new Windows 7 tablet at this year's CES.

But even beyond the success of Windows 7, which has sold over 240 million copies, Microsoft's fortunes are turning around elsewhere, too. After failures in other product areas  remember the Kin and the Zune?  Microsoft has a big win with Kinect, this year's must-have holiday gadget. And Windows Phone 7 has received glowing reviews (though hasn't yet achieved iPhone-type sales figures). And though Microsoft's Bing search engine still trails Google by a wide margin, it now powers Yahoo, and now accounts for 12 percent of searches.

When asked recently when he could be expected to retire, he replied, "I've got a lot of energy and passion for what I'm doing. If I ever thought there was a day when the company would be better off without me, I'd leave that day." Michael Muchmore







6



Share
Tweet
Pin
Email

6. Andy Rubin, Google

Andy Rubin doesn't speak out much because he wants the Android community to do most of the talking. His hands-off approach to the OS he helped design, and now runs, for Google has led it to tremendous success: Android is everywhere, vaulting beyond BlackBerry and Apple to take the No. 1 spot in U.S. smartphone sales. Behind its success is Rubin's vision of an OS that's "open" enough for carriers to customize it, but where Google sets a few key ground rules for support of the company's much-loved apps.

Now that Android on phones seems to be refining itself rather than leaping forwards, Rubin has turned his focus to Honeycomb, the new version of Android designed for tablets. His task in 2011 will be to see whether he can keep the delicate balance of his own vision, his carrier partners, and mobile manufacturers intact  and whether he can use that to conquer the tablet market the way Android has swept over phones. Sascha Segan







7



Share
Tweet
Pin
Email

7. Reed Hastings, Netflix

Reed Hastings, the fifty-year-old chief executive of Netflix, has suckered Hollywood. Twice.

First, Hastings sweet-talked Hollywood into giving him access to its collective DVD library reportedly for less than what cable services paid. Meanwhile, Hastings convinced consumers to accept waiting a day or two for DVDs by sending them via low-cost snail mail, rather than running to the video store. For a second act, Hastings and Netflix began streaming the titles directly to consumer devices like TVs, Blu-ray players and set-top boxes  incidentally forcing former video titans like Blockbuster into bankruptcy. Then, Hastings cut deals with distributors like FilmDistrict and Starz, rather than the studios themselves, for the rights to top Hollywood hits.

Why does Hastings matter? Because he controls a key distribution channel to the home  and, according to some, hasn't yet paid the piper. Hollywood studios all want their piece of the pie, and it will be up to Hastings to keep costs down while maintaining Netflix's role as a gatekeeper to Hollywood content. As Netflix ventures deeper into on-demand distribution, it would be wise for Hastings to heed the lessons CinemaNow, a streaming movie company that went belly-up. Will he? Ask us again in a year. Mark Hachman







8



Share
Tweet
Pin
Email

8. Julius Genachowski, FCC

It's been an interesting year for Julius Genachowski. Since coming on board as Federal Communications Commission chairman last year, Genachowski has focused on a number of high-profile tech issues, from a national broadband plan to Net Neutrality.

And while Genachowski deals with dozens of tech issues on any given day, Net Neutrality has the potential to be the most controversial topic with which he contends this year. Since April, when an appeals court threw the FCC's authority to regulate broadband into question, Genachowski and the FCC legal team have been working furiously to establish a precedent for the agency's authority over the issue, which is how the majority of Americans now access the Internet. Earlier this week, a revamped plan was approved by a vote of 3-2, but Congress might challenge those rules come January.
Beyond Net Neutrality, however, Genachowski has presided over the congressionally mandated national broadband plan, opened up TV "white spaces" for unlicensed "super" Wi-Fi, begun investigations into various wireless issues like "bill shock," and more recently, stepped into the licensing battles between cable companies and broadcasters. It's been a busy year for Genachowski, though if his efforts all bear fruit, 2011 will be even bigger. Chloe Albanesius









9



Share
Tweet
Pin
Email

9. Brian Hogan

Yep, that Brian Hogan  the young man who allegedly found a certain prototype phone in a Redwood City, CA, bar and took it upon himself to fence his questionably gotten gains to a upstart tech blog. Hogan may not have guided any billion-dollar companies like others on this list, but by taking what was clearly a top-secret device and putting it in the hands of the media, he effectively smeared egg all over the face of one.

Whereas Gray Powell, the Apple engineer who lost the prototype, really just made an honest (if careless) mistake, the first conscious decision that led to the premature revelation of the iPhone 4 was Hogan's. His 15 minutes have long since expired, but he'll live forever in Internet archives, and Gizmodo has a lot to thank him for, since the $5,000 it spent on the device resulted in millions of page views, briefly making the site a staple of mainstream newscasts and talk-show monologues.

If sales and stock prices are any indication, Apple didn't suffer from the ordeal. But Internet fanboys may have a bone to pick with Hogan, as his big reveal robbed them of weeks of idle speculation and Photoshopped guesses to what the iPhone 4 would be. To others, that may make him a hero. Peter Pachal







10



Share
Tweet
Pin
Email

10. Elon Musk, SpaceX

SpaceX's founder, CEO, and CTO had a year that was out of this world, as SpaceX launched an unmanned Falcon 9 rocket where no private-sector spacecraft had gone before: to orbit and safely home.

Even as President Obama's February proposal to replace the Space Shuttle with private-sector spacecraft was met largely with ridicule, the 39-year-old Musk was demonstrating commercial space flight's potential. In June and again in December, the company lofted Falcon 9 rockets into orbit from Cape Canaveral. In the second test, a SpaceX Dragon capsule circled the Earth twice before parachuting into the Pacific Ocean where it was recovered, the first orbital flight and recovery ever by a nongovernmental entity.

SpaceX  which has a $1.6 billion NASA contract  is one of two companies (the other is Orbital Sciences) selected by the space agency to launch unmanned supply missions to the International Space Station (ISS); the first two are planned for late 2011. The company is also retooling the Dragon capsule for eventual manned flights, though it's still a long road to a viable Space Shuttle replacement. Tony Hoffman







